# Shapiro-Wilk Test

from scipy.stats import shapiro

stat, p = shapiro(cleanerdf["deaths by county population"])
print('Statistics=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (stat, p))
# interpret
alpha = 0.05
if p > alpha:
	print('Normally distributed')
else:
	print('Not Normal')

from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.model_selection import RepeatedKFold
from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge
from numpy import mean
from numpy import absolute
from numpy import around
In [287]:
model = Ridge(alpha=1.0)  # assigning a ridge regression algorithm to my model
In [288]:
cv=RepeatedKFold(n_splits=10,n_repeats=3,random_state=1)  #assigning a cross validation method
In [289]:
scores = cross_val_score(model, x, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=-1)  #executing the crossvalidation machine learning and obtaining the R Squared score
In [290]:
n=len(y)          #obtaining the adjusted R-Squared
p=len(xcolumns)
adj_scores=1-(1-scores)*(n-1)/(n-p-1)
In [291]:
scores_MSE = cross_val_score(model, x, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=-1, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error') #obtaining the mean square error
In [292]:
scores_MAE= cross_val_score(model, x, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=-1, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error') #obtaining the mean absolute error
In [293]:
scores_RMSE= cross_val_score(model, x, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=-1, scoring='neg_root_mean_squared_error') #obtaining the root mean squared error
In [294]:

In [347]:
### obtainging the adjusted R Squared scores
n=len(y)
p=len(xcolumns)
adj_scores=1-(1-scores)*(n-1)/(n-p-1)
In [348]:

In [349]:

In [350]:
